re the final countdown."), mdx("p", null, "There are some quite strict rules climbing Matterhorn from the hut. You can't just randomly ascend it whenever you want, there is defined time when you can start, at the end of a season it was quite late - earliest time was at 4:50. Also one more rule - groups with Swiss guides go first, then groups with other country guides and individual groups go last. Those all rules make sense to ensure the efficient and safe climb for everyone, but that definitely didn't help us to achieve our initial plan and it was quite obvious that we will not make it until 17:00 o'clock to the cable car. But there were other option like to stay at the hut for one more night or just descent way back to Zermatt (1608m) which is kind of hardcore, but doable, so we didn't bother to much about that."), mdx("p", null, "We woke up at 4:20, had a breakfast, prepared all gear needed and headed to the start of the climb. We knew that there will be small jam at the beginning because there were around 20 other groups climbing, mostly with guides and first section is steep and slow with fixed ropes, so we were not in a big rush as we will still climb last. Standing in a queue for the climb was a bit nervous, many random thoughts came to my mind, but as soon as we started to climb everything just vanished. Love so much that feeling of focus and clarity of what to do next while climbing. It is so awesome when your body, mind and feelings supplement each other and all contributes to the same goal."), mdx("p", null, "Our pace was super fast, we run through the first half of the climb in no time beating all our expectations. Following rushing guides with their clients and random roommates shouts \"Go, go, room number 12!!!\" surely helps to keep motivation up and not give up when it gets harder. We did a small rest by the emergency Solvay hut (4000m), enjoyed stunning view of the landscape and made ourselves ready for the final vertical meters of the climb. This part was much steeper, more difficult technically and we already felt a bit tiredness after so intense climbing. Our pace slowed down a little, we dropped behind a bit from the main group we were following and that's the point where things get a bit more interesting. :)"), mdx("p", null, "\"Rock!!!\" - never heard Ignas shouting this word so seriously. We often encounter small falling rock while rock climbing, but most of them are not significant to worry about and would give you a bruise on contact at most, despite this fact it's still a good habit to warn everyone about incoming dangers. But that one was from a different league. One that could easily wipe off few people at once! Gladly it passed by me and another group that was climbing behind us and everyone stayed safe. That was a good indicator that we should be extremely careful with our chosen path as rocks are very fragile even few meters off the main track and that could be fatal not only for us, but for others as well."), mdx("p", null, "A little bit shocked but determined to finish our challenge we proceeded with our climb more carefully. Terrain was getting steeper and steeper. We approached one of the last sections of the climb - fixed ropes. As at the very beginning of the climb there were almost vertical walls with massive ropes attached to them. The section itself was quite long and some groups were already descending the mountain so it get more difficult to proceed fast, but there were time to realise what is happening and just look around. So much was clearly visible at once - whole ridge that we climbed, Hornli hut where we stayed last night and even Zermatt village. It's truly amazing to realise that so much climb was already in the past and we are almost on the top. But from the other side we knew that hardest part awaits ahead - last section of snowy 50 degree slab and then descent way back from the mountain which usually takes longer than ascend."), mdx("p", null, "Rope by rope we approached the last section which at least for me was the scariest part of the climb. Basically you have only crampons and ice axe to hold on to, rocks - which was the main holding point the whole route, here were rarely visible. One uncertain movement, one slipped ice axe and you are sliding down the slope. Of course, we used our rope for safety purposes, but you would still slide 10-20 meters down on inaccurate move. I was impressed how determined and certain @Ignas was on this last part of a climb. That attitude of him for sure helped me as well to get my shit together and just work for our goal which was that close."), mdx("p", null, "Finally! The summit! Walking through top ridge felt like walking on a podium after winning some grand worldwide competition. And the award was the best I could ever imagine. The landscape of the whole Alps. Switzerland on one side, Italy on the other and you are walking on a tiny edge of this whole mesmerising exposure, all filled with emotions that can't be expressed by any words."));
